abstract.p: This paper is motivated by a general question: for which values of k𝑘 and n𝑛 is the universal Burnside kei Q¯⁢(k,n)¯𝑄𝑘𝑛 finite? It is known (starting from the work of M. Takasaki (1942)) that Q¯⁢(2,n)¯𝑄2𝑛 is isomorphic to the dihedral quandle Znsubscript𝑍𝑛and Q¯⁢(3,3)¯𝑄33 is isomorphic to Z3⊕Z3direct-sumsubscript𝑍3subscript𝑍3. In this paper we give descriptions of Q¯⁢(4,3)¯𝑄43 and Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34. We also investigate some properties of arbitrary quandles satisfying the universal Burnside relation a=…⁢a*b*…*a*b𝑎…𝑎𝑏…𝑎𝑏. In particular, we prove that the order of a finite commutative kei is a power of 3. Invariants of links related to Burnside kei Q¯⁢(k,n)¯𝑄𝑘𝑛 are invariant under n𝑛-moves.

div.head: Introduction
div.p: Kei, , also called an involutory quandle, was introduced by Mituhisa Takasaki in 1942 [Tak] as an abstract algebra (Q,*)𝑄 with a binary operation *:Q×Q→Qfragments:QQ→Q satisfying the conditions:

We adopt the standard convention (the left normed convention) that omission of parentheses denotes the left association, for example a*b*c𝑎𝑏𝑐 denotes (a*b)*c𝑎𝑏𝑐. The above axioms correspond to the Reidemeister moves (see Fig. 1).We consider free keis with the universal relation:
rnsubscript𝑟𝑛:a=…⁢a*b*…*a*b𝑎…𝑎𝑏…𝑎𝑏,

in which there are n𝑛 letters on the right hand side and a𝑎, b𝑏 are any elements of the kei. We denote such kei with k𝑘 generators as Q¯⁢(k,n)¯𝑄𝑘𝑛 and call it the universal Burnside kei.In [Joy] D. Joyce associated an involutory quandle to a link. In a similar way we can associate to every link its n𝑛-th Burnside kei, Q¯n⁢(L)subscript¯𝑄𝑛𝐿, by assigning generators to arcs of the diagram of L𝐿, writing the relation of the form u*v=w𝑢𝑣𝑤 for each crossing (here u𝑢 and w𝑤 are generators corresponding to the under-arcs and v𝑣 is assigned to the over-arc) and adding the universal relation rnsubscript𝑟𝑛.Relation rnsubscript𝑟𝑛 corresponds to the local changes in the diagram called n𝑛-moves. It follows that Q¯n⁢(L)subscript¯𝑄𝑛𝐿 is invariant under Reidemeister moves and n𝑛-moves. For example, r3subscript𝑟3:a=b*a*b𝑎𝑏𝑎𝑏 corresponds to invariance under 33-moves and r4subscript𝑟4:a=a*b*a*b𝑎𝑎𝑏𝑎𝑏 makes Q¯4⁢(L)subscript¯𝑄4𝐿 invariant under 44-moves. Fig. 2 illustrates this correspondence in the case n=3𝑛3, 44. In fact, Q¯n⁢(L)subscript¯𝑄𝑛𝐿 is also invariant under rational nm𝑛𝑚-moves [D-I-P].

div.p: Every algebraically connected quandle (not necessarily involutory) is a metric space if we define the metric d⁢(x,y)𝑑𝑥𝑦 as the minimal number of operators needed to obtain one element from the other. A significant class of algebraically connected quandles are knot quandles (see [Joy] for a definition). Since our metric is unchanged under isomorphism of quandles, some metric properties (for example diameter) are knot invariants. p.hi: The order of a finite commutative kei Q𝑄 is a power of 33.

note.title: Proof.
note.p: Let a𝑎, b𝑏 denote any two elements of Q𝑄 and let P𝑃 be the three element subquandle {a,b,a*b}𝑎𝑏𝑎𝑏. From the right distributivity property it follows that for any element x∈Q𝑥𝑄, the set S:=P*x={a*x,b*x,(a*b)*x}assign𝑆𝑃𝑥𝑎𝑥𝑏𝑥𝑎𝑏𝑥 is also a subquandle. We ask the following question: what other elements of Q𝑄 send P𝑃 to S𝑆 ? There can be at most three such operators, sending a𝑎 to a*x𝑎𝑥, b*x𝑏𝑥 or (a*b)*x𝑎𝑏𝑥 (here we use the fact that two operators x𝑥, y∈Q𝑦𝑄 acting in the same way on one element are the same). Using lemma 2 we can find them easily:
From the left distributivity it follows that the set of these three operators is a subquandle. We still need to check that operators (2) and (3) send b𝑏 and a*b𝑎𝑏 to S𝑆:

In this way we obtain a partition of Q𝑄 into 3-element disjoint subquandles of the form {x,x*b*a,x*a*b}𝑥𝑥𝑏𝑎𝑥𝑎𝑏, in which two elements belong to the same triple if they send P𝑃 to the same subquandle. This relation between elements is an equivalence relation but not a congruence (u∼vsimilar-to𝑢𝑣, s∼tsimilar-to𝑠𝑡 does not imply (u*s)∼(v*t)similar-to𝑢𝑠𝑣𝑡), so we cannot simply form a quotient quandle. Instead, we define a natural quandle operation, *^^, on triples:

The set of such triples, with operation *^^, forms a commutative kei that is three times smaller than the original kei, Q𝑄. Thus we can use the inductive argument to conclude that the size of Q𝑄 is a power of 33. ∎

div.p: It was shown by M. Takasaki [Tak] that Q¯⁢(2,n)¯𝑄2𝑛 is isomorphic to the dihedral quandle Znsubscript𝑍𝑛 and Q¯⁢(3,3)¯𝑄33 is isomorphic to Z3⊕Z3direct-sumsubscript𝑍3subscript𝑍3. Here we give a description of Q¯⁢(4,3)¯𝑄43.T.Ohtsuki wrote a computer program which helps to analyze the commutative kei. Using this program he found that Q¯⁢(4,3)¯𝑄43 has 8181 elements. A different computation, involving operator group of the quandle, was made by the first author. Here we follow, in a crucial point, Ohtsuki’s approach to obtain a computer free proof.

As noted by Takasaki, every element of the kei can be written in a left-normed form (usually not uniquely). div.p: The primary examples of keis satisfying the fourth Burnside relation, x=x*y*x*y𝑥𝑥𝑦𝑥𝑦, are the dihedral kei Z4subscript𝑍4, its direct sums, and the fourth Burnside groups and their quotients (with the core operation x*y=yx-1y)fragmentsxyysuperscript𝑥1y).To get the lower bound on the order of Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34, we can consider the group with presentation:

where x𝑥 and y𝑦 are any conjugates of generators a𝑎, b𝑏, c𝑐. We checked (with the help of GAP) that this group has 8192=2138192superscript213 elements and the size of the union of conjugacy classes of generators is 9696. The elements of these conjugacy classes form a 33-generator quandle (with conjugation as operation *) satisfying the relation x=x*y*x*y𝑥𝑥𝑦𝑥𝑦. Thus the order of the free kei Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34 cannot be less than 9696. This time we cannot use the Lemma 3 to obtain the upper bound for the size of Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34 (compare with the remark after the proof of Theorem 6), so instead we will build a Cayley diagram for this quandle. This diagram has 9696 vertices, therefore Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34 has order 9696. Below we calculate some relations needed to build such a diagram. Again, we use brackets [] to stress which parts of words properties of Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34 are used on. None of these properties can replace the first letter in the left normed representatives of words in Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34. For example a left normed word starting with a𝑎 never equals to the word starting with b𝑏. It follows that the diagram will consist of three disjoint parts that look the same when viewed as graphs (see Figure 3).

div.p: One of the oldest conjectures concerning local changes in the diagram is the Nakanishi conjecture (see [Prz]).

p.hi: Every knot is 44-move equivalent to the trivial knot.

div.p: Our hope was that the fourth Burnside kei of the knot can be used to detect a potential counterexample to this conjecture. However, the following theorem suggests this is not likely to be the case.

p.hi: Every algebraically connected quotient of Q¯⁢(3,4)normal-¯𝑄34 is a trivial, one element quandle.

note.title: Proof.
note.p: Let Q~~𝑄 be the algebraically connected quotient of Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34, f:Q¯⁢(3,4)→Q~:𝑓→¯𝑄34~𝑄 be the quotient homomorphism and S1subscript𝑆1, S2subscript𝑆2, S3subscript𝑆3 denote the algebraically connected components of Q¯⁢(3,4)¯𝑄34 .We claim that Q~~𝑄 is contained in each image f⁢(Si)𝑓subscript𝑆𝑖, for i=1, 2, 3𝑖1 2 3.By the way of contradiction, let us assume that there exists x∈Q~𝑥~𝑄 and f-1⁢(x)∩Sj=∅superscript𝑓1𝑥subscript𝑆𝑗, for some j𝑗. Let a𝑎 be any element of Sjsubscript𝑆𝑗 and y=f⁢(a)𝑦𝑓𝑎. Then from the algebraic connectivity of Q~~𝑄 follows that x=y*x1*…*xk𝑥𝑦subscript𝑥1…subscript𝑥𝑘, for some elements x1,…,xk∈Q~subscript𝑥1…subscript𝑥𝑘~𝑄. Now we choose arbitrary elements zisubscript𝑧𝑖 from the preimages f-1⁢(xi)superscript𝑓1subscript𝑥𝑖, i=1,…,k𝑖1…𝑘. Let z=a*z1*…*zk𝑧𝑎subscript𝑧1…subscript𝑧𝑘. Then z∈Sj𝑧subscript𝑆𝑗 and f⁢(z)=f⁢(a)*f⁢(z1)*…*f⁢(zk)=y*x1*…*xk=x𝑓𝑧𝑓𝑎𝑓subscript𝑧1…𝑓subscript𝑧𝑘𝑦subscript𝑥1…subscript𝑥𝑘𝑥, which contradicts the original assumption that f-1⁢(x)∩Sj=∅superscript𝑓1𝑥subscript𝑆𝑗.Each subquandle Sisubscript𝑆𝑖, when considered as a quandle itself, has eight 44-element components (orbits), T1,…,T8subscript𝑇1…subscript𝑇8 and just as before, we can prove that Q~~𝑄 is the image of each Tisubscript𝑇𝑖 (and can have at most 4 elements). But finally we can use the fact that every such Tisubscript𝑇𝑖 is a trivial quandle (x*y=x𝑥𝑦𝑥, for any x𝑥, y∈Ti𝑦subscript𝑇𝑖) and Q~~𝑄 must be an image of just one element. ∎

div.p: Since knot quandles are algebraically connected, we have the following result.

p.hi: Let K𝐾 be a knot such that the minimal number of generators of its fundamental quandle is ≤3absent3. Then its fourth Burnside quandle, Q¯4⁢(K)subscriptnormal-¯𝑄4𝐾, has only one element.

div.p: For example, Q¯4⁢(K)subscript¯𝑄4𝐾 will not detect a potential counterexample to the Nakanishi 44-move conjecture among 33-bridge knots.It seems to be plausible that the order of Q¯4⁢(K)subscript¯𝑄4𝐾 is 11, for any knot K𝐾.
